[2026-03-18T11:31:48.408Z] [STDOUT] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CfwUV6C12xtJgF22dD9jpy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WL2ufMGFZtmRkA4TtmTGp7","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/ideas \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"scan_id\": \"c7195383-d4af-459b-9ca4-602fc28de84d\",\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"scan_type\": \"moonshot_architect\",\n    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n    \"title\": \"Adaptive sandbox that learns and self-tunes policies\",\n    \"description\": \"Build an intelligence layer over the sandbox and network proxy that observes execution patterns across runs and automatically optimizes. It would analyze network proxy logs to suggest minimal allow-list policies, track resource usage to auto-tune timeout and budget limits, detect anomalous behavior (unexpected network destinations, excessive stderr, credential access patterns outside norms) and flag it via the manual_review protocol, and progressively tighten sandbox permissions based on observed behavior profiles. First sprint: add a PolicySuggester module that records all proxy CONNECT targets during execution and emits a suggested NetworkPolicy as a new protocol event type at completion.\",\n    \"reasoning\": \"Security policies are currently static and manually configured. Most users will either over-restrict (breaking functionality) or under-restrict (creating risk). An adaptive system that watches real behavior and suggests optimal policies would make the platform self-securing — the more it runs, the safer it gets. This creates a compounding strategic moat: every execution makes the platform smarter about what constitutes normal vs anomalous persona behavior.\",\n    \"effort\": 8,\n    \"impact\": 9,\n    \"risk\": 7\n  }'","description":"Save idea 5 without context_id"},"caller":{"type":"direct"